Data Visualization¶

The users can check the top ten countries based on number of the brands such as: Japan, USA, South Korea, Taiwan, Thailand, China, Malaysia, Hong Kong, Indonesia, Singapore. The users can check the styles, brands, and flavors of ramen for the top 10 countries. Also, they can see the top 10 countries with highest stars.

We also include the graphs for the total consumption of ramen from 2014 - 2018 for the top 10 countries (We do not import this dataset. Instead, we created a dataframe for each country)

Searching¶

This small program allows the users to see a report for a specific country that they enter. The users has 4 options:

Option 1: Displaying all information and graphs.

Option 2: Displaying brand, country, and stars.

Option 3: Displaying brand, variety, style, and country.

Option 4: Write to csv file (Please remember to enter .csv at the end)

Option 5: Prediction markets. If the temperature is below or 20 degree Celsius, we predict the customers will buy ramen. If the temperature is above 20 degree Celsius, we predict the customers will not buy ramen.

In [48]:
def function1():
    ask = input("Please enter any country: ")
    c = rf[rf.Country == ask]
    df = pd.DataFrame(c)
    print(df.to_string())
    #style plot
    style = c.Style.value_counts()
    style.plot.pie(autopct="%1.0f%%")
    plt.axis("tight")
    plt.title("STYLES OF RAMEN IN " + ask.upper())
    plt.show()
    #brand plot
    brand = c.Brand.value_counts().head(10)
    brand.plot.barh(color=["steelblue", "orange", "green", "red", "purple", "brown", "pink", "gray", "olive", "cyan"])
    plt.title("TOP 10 BRANDS OF RAMEN IN " + ask.upper())
    plt.show()
    #variety plot
    variety = c.Variety.value_counts().head(10)
    variety.plot.barh(color=["steelblue", "orange", "green", "red", "purple", "brown", "pink", "gray", "olive", "cyan"])
    plt.title("TOP 10 FLAVOR OF RAMEN IN " + ask.upper())
    plt.show()
def function2():
    ask = input("Please enter any country: ")
    c = rf[rf.Country == ask]
    df = pd.DataFrame(c)
    df = df[["Brand", "Country", "Stars"]]
    print(df.to_string())
def function3():
    ask = input("Please enter any country: ")
    c = rf[rf.Country == ask]
    df = pd.DataFrame(c)
    df = df[["Brand", "Variety", "Style", "Country"]]
    print(df.to_string())
def function4():
    ask = input("Please enter any country: ")
    c = rf[rf.Country == ask]
    out = input("Enter the name of the file:")
    df = pd.DataFrame(c)
    df.set_index("Review #", inplace=True)
    df.to_csv(out)
def function5():
    woeid = 0
    t = 0
    #Finding woeid
    query = input("Enter a city: ").strip().replace(" ", "+")
    urlBase = "https://www.metaweather.com/api/location/"
    urlSearch = urlBase + "search?query=" + query
    uh = urllib.request.urlopen(urlSearch)
    data = uh.read().decode()
    js = json.loads(data)
    for k in js:
        woeid = k["woeid"]
        print("woeid: " + str(woeid))       
    #Finding date    
    date = input("Please enter the date (Format for the date: yyyy/mm/dd): ")
    urlRetrieve = urlBase + str(woeid) + "/" + str(date) + "/"
    uhRetrieve = urllib.request.urlopen(urlRetrieve)
    data2 = uhRetrieve.read().decode()
    js2 = json.loads(data2)
    for k in js2:
        w = k["weather_state_name"]
        t = k["the_temp"]
    print("The temperature on " + str(date) + " is: " + str(t) + " degree Celsius. The weather is " + str(w))
    if t <= 20:
        print("The customers will buy ramen")
    elif t > 20:
        print("The customers will not buy ramen")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    cy = input(" 1: Displaying all infomation and graphs.\n 2: Displaying brand, country, and stars.\n 3: Displaying brand, variety, style, and country.\n 4: Write to csv file.\n 5: Prediction markets.\n Your choice is:  ")
    if cy == "1":
        function1()
    elif cy == "2":
        function2()
    elif cy == "3":
        function3()
    elif cy == "4":
        function4()
    elif cy == "5":
        function5()

Object-oriented programming¶

In [46]:
#Composition 
class Country:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
        self.varieties = []
        
    def add_variety(self, variety):
        self.varieties.append(variety)
        
class Brand:
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
        self.flavors = []
    
    def add_flavor(self, name, style, star):
        variety = Variety(name, style, self, star)
        self.flavors.append(variety)
        
class Variety:
    def __init__(self, name, style, brand, star):
        self.name = name
        self.style = style
        self.brand = brand
        self.star = star

#Japan
japan_brand = Brand("Sapporo Ichiban")
japan_brand.add_flavor("Chow Mein", "Pack", 5)
japan_brand.add_flavor("Shrimp Flavor", "Pack", 2.5)
japan_brand.add_flavor("Miso Soybean Paste", "Pack", 3.5)
japan = Country("Japan")
for f in japan_brand.flavors:
    japan.add_variety(f)
    print("Country: " + japan.name + " Brand: " + japan_brand.name + " Variety: " + f.name + " Style: " + f.style + " Star: " + str(f.star))
